{"id":"0812.2477","submitter":"Jesse Thaler","authors":"Martin Schmaltz, Jesse Thaler","title":"Collective Quartics and Dangerous Singlets in Little Higgs","comments":"4 pages; v2: clarified the existing literature; v3: version to appear\n  in JHEP","journal-ref":"JHEP 0903:137,2009","doi":"10.1088/1126-6708/2009/03/137","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Any extension of the standard model that aims to describe TeV-scale physics\nwithout fine-tuning must have a radiatively-stable Higgs potential. In little\nHiggs theories, radiative stability is achieved through so-called collective\nsymmetry breaking. In this letter, we focus on the necessary conditions for a\nlittle Higgs to have a collective Higgs quartic coupling. In one-Higgs doublet\nmodels, a collective quartic requires an electroweak triplet scalar. In\ntwo-Higgs doublet models, a collective quartic requires a triplet or singlet\nscalar. As a corollary of this study, we show that some little Higgs theories\nhave dangerous singlets, a pathology where collective symmetry breaking does\nnot suppress quadratically-divergent corrections to the Higgs mass.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Dec 2008 20:22:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 14 Jan 2009 18:16:40 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 30 Mar 2009 01:22:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-04-30"}
